Background and problem ¶

Oslo is the fastest-growing capital city in all of Europe. It has around 680,000 friendly people, a strong economy, and great connectivity to the wonderful nature. Oslo is clearly undergoing great change these years and more than 40,000 move into the city each year, according to the Oslo Kommune. Such mobility is expected to continue in the coming years.

Finding a right place to live is non-trivial, especially for those who have never been to Oslo before. People have various preferences on the neighborhoods they want to live in. It would be very helpful if we are able to segment and characterize the neighborhoods in Oslo and provide some clue of where to live for potential new comers based on the similarity between the neighborhoods they are currently living in (or they like) with the neighborhoods in Oslo. Popular housing portals in Norway like Finn.no can think about to provide such service to their potential new users.

Data description ¶

To tackle the above problem, I will need neighborhood data, coordinates of the neighborhoods, and data of venues (e.g. cafe, restaurant) in each neighborhood of Oslo.

The neighborhood data consists of names, average housing prices, area sizes and populations of the neighborhoods. This data is made public by the Oslo Kommune. The coordinates of the neighborhoods can be easily found from Google Maps via its API. The venue data consists of names, addresses, types, etc. of popular venues in each neighborhood. Such data can be obtained from Foursquare by using the Foursquare API.

These pieces of data will be combined and used to segment and characterize neighborhoods in Oslo. The k-means clustering algorithm will be employed to perform this task. Finally, I will predict where you want to live in Oslo if you are from the neighborhood of Chelsea, London!

Collecting the neighborhood and population data ¶

The website of Oslo Kommune, where we get neighborhood data from, is very interactive. To get the table of the population data, one click of the table button is required. So it's not possible to crawl the data using the Requests and BuiltfulSoup libraries which enable us to crawl data from static webpages. Instead, I use Selenium which gets data by mimicking human web browsing behavior.

In [3]:
url_oslo_kommune = r'https://bydelsfakta.oslo.kommune.no/'
In [4]:
# open the website of Oslo Kommune
options = webdriver.ChromeOptions()
browser_path = r'E:\Downloads\chromedriver_win32\chromedriver'
browser = webdriver.Chrome(browser_path, options=options)
browser.get(url_oslo_kommune)

I need to first get the list of bydel and their specific webpages (I keep the Norwegian word 'Bydel' in the codes and the report instead of its English counterpart 'Borough' since it's shorter).

In [5]:
bydel_urls = {}
attempts, attempted = 3, 0
while True:
    bydels_list = browser.find_elements_by_class_name('navigation-link__label')
    for bydel in bydels_list:
        bydel_name = bydel.text
        bydel_url = bydel.get_attribute('href')
        bydel_urls[bydel_name] = bydel_url
    attempted += 1
    if len(bydel_urls) != 0 | attempted == attempts:
        break

assert len(bydel_urls) != 0, f"Tried {attempts} times, but didn't get the links of the bydels."
for k, v in bydel_urls.items():
    print(k, v)

Once the webpages of all the bydels are found, I will iterate through them and find the neighborhoods in each bydel and their population data. It takes a bit time to open these webpages and get data from them, so a progress bar is implemented to show the current progress.

In [6]:
results_bydels = []
progress_bar = tqdm(bydel_urls)

# get data for each bydel
for bydel in progress_bar:
    progress_bar.set_description(f'Getting data of {bydel} ...')
    result_bydel = []
    # open bydel webpage and find the data table by clicking the table button
    browser.get(bydel_urls[bydel]+'/befolkningsutvikling')
    browser.find_element_by_xpath("//button[@aria-label='Tabell']").click()
    # try 3 time maximum if having StaleElementReferenceException
    attempts, attempted = 3, 0
    while True:
        try:
            while True:
                table = browser.find_element_by_tag_name('tbody').find_elements_by_tag_name('tr')
                if len(table) != 0:
                    break
            for row in table:
                nei_name = row.find_element_by_tag_name('th').text
                # change the number in code below to change year
                nei_pop = row.find_elements_by_tag_name('td')[-1].text                
                result_bydel.append([bydel, nei_name, nei_pop])
        except StaleElementReferenceException:
            attempted += 1
            if attempted == attempts:
                print(f'--- Already tried {attempted} times ---')
                raise
            else:
                result_bydel = []
        else:
            results_bydels += result_bydel
            break

Let's see how many bydels and neighborhoods are there in Oslo.

In [14]:
print('There are {} bydels and {} neighborhoods in Oslo.'.format(
    len(df['Bydel'].unique()), len(df['Neighborhood'].unique())))

There are 15 bydels and 96 neighborhoods in Oslo.

Note: Officially, Oslo city has 98 neighborhoods or 15 bydels in addition to two special parts to be more precise. The two neighborhoods excluded in this data are Sentrum and Marka. Sentrum is literally the very center of Oslo while Marka is the large forest area surrounding Oslo. Both of them are not administrative unit. People living at Sentrum receive administrative services at St. Hanshaugen and people living at Marka receive administrative services from the nearest bydels.

def str2int(s):
    """Convert number in string s format to int. Assign NaN value if ValueError raised."""
    try:
        number = int(s)
    except ValueError:
        number = np.nan
    return number

People do use these neighborhood names these days, at least Helsfyr and Økern are heard lots of times. In fact, the neighborhoods in Oslo were revised in 2017, according to the Oslo Kommune. Specifically,

  • Lodalen was divided into Kværnerbyen and Bispevika.
  • Helsfyr became Ensjø and Etterstad.
  • Hasle-Løren were seperated to Hasle and Løren.
  • Økern became Refstad and Ulven.

Let's see if the new neighborhoods (i.e. Kvaernerbyen, Bispevika, Ensjø, Etterstad, Hasle, Løren, Refstad and Ulven) are in the data or not.

Adding coordinates ¶

It's very convenient to obtain coordinates from Google Maps by using its Python library. All you need is a Google Maps API key and a few lines of code.

In [49]:
# the key is private and removed after running all the codes
gmaps = googlemaps.Client(key='***')
In [50]:
# get coordinates
oslo = 'Oslo, Norway'
coor = []

for idx, row in df.iterrows():
    where = row.Neighborhood + ', ' + oslo
    geo_result = gmaps.geocode(where)
    lat = geo_result[0]['geometry']['location']['lat']
    long = geo_result[0]['geometry']['location']['lng']
    coor.append((lat, long))

assert len(coor) != 0, "Didn't get the coordinates from Google Maps."

In [61]:
def oslo_map(data, feature, colors, city_location):
    """Show on a Folium map a feature of Oslo that range from relatively low values to 
    relatively high values. Darker color indicates higher value.
    
    Keyword arguments:
    data - a Pandas Dataframe
    feature - name of a numeric feature
    colors - a Seaborn palette
    city_location - coordinates of the city
    """
    map_o = folium.Map(location=city_location, zoom_start=10)    
    # add markers of neighborhoods in Oslo    
    for idx, row in data.sort_values(feature).reset_index().iterrows():
        folium.CircleMarker(
        location=[row.Latitude, row.Longitude],
        radius=5,
        popup=f'{row.Neighborhood}, {row[feature]}',
        color=None,
        fill=True,
        fill_color=mpl.colors.to_hex(colors[idx]),
        fill_opacity=1.0).add_to(map_o)
    return map_o

def get_category_type(row):
    """Extract the category of the venue."""
    try:
        categories_list = row['categories']
    except:
        categories_list = row['venue.categories']
        
    if len(categories_list) == 0:
        return None
    else:
        return categories_list[0]['name']

In [74]:
def getNearbyVenues(names, latitudes, longitudes, radius=2000):
    """Get all the nearby venues for all the neighborhoods from Foursquare. Return a Pandas
    Dataframe containing the folowing features: 
    ['Neighborhood', 'Neighborhood Latitude', 'Neighborhood Longitude', 'Venue', 
    'Venue Latitude', 'Venue Longitude', 'Venue Category'].
    """
    venues_list = []
    
    for name, lat, lng in zip(names, latitudes, longitudes):            
        # create the API request URL
        url = r'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&limit={}'
        url = url.format(CLIENT_ID, CLIENT_SECRET, VERSION, lat, lng, radius, LIMIT)            
        # make the GET request
        results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']        
        # return only relevant information for each nearby venue
        venues_list.append([(
            name, lat, lng, 
            v['venue']['name'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lat'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lng'],  
            v['venue']['categories'][0]['name']) for v in results])

    nearby_venues = pd.DataFrame([item for venue_list in venues_list for item in venue_list])
    nearby_venues.columns = ['Neighborhood', 
                  'Neighborhood Latitude', 
                  'Neighborhood Longitude', 
                  'Venue', 
                  'Venue Latitude', 
                  'Venue Longitude', 
                  'Venue Category']    
    return nearby_venues

Building k-means clustering model¶

I will be using k-means clustering algorithm to segment the neighborhoods in Oslo based on their similarities. This classic algorithm is relatively simple to implement, and it scales to large data sets, guarantees convergence and adapts to new examples easily.

Before running the k-means, we need to manually specify the desired number of clusters, k. Since there is no clear hint of the best k in the case, I simply try different numbers ranging from 1 to 20 and see what k is good choice based on the elbow method.

The elbow method gives an idea on how to choose a good k based on the total point-to-centroid distance. As k, the number of clusters increases, clusters become smaller and the total distance decreases. We choose the k where the total distance starts to flatten out and forming an elbow, as any larger number gives marginal performance gain.

In [96]:
cost = []
ks = range(1, 20)
for k in ks:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=0).fit(data_clustering)
    kmeans.labels_
    cost.append(kmeans.inertia_)
In [97]:
fig = plt.plot(ks, cost)
plt.xticks(ks)
plt.xlabel('K - Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Total point-to-centroid distance')
plt.show()

The above figure suggests 6, 7 and 8 are good k. So let's take a number in the middle and segment the neighborhoods in Oslo into 7 clusters and plot the result on a map.

The table above provides the mean of each feature for each cluster. You can figure out the characteristics of the clusters by studying the numbers. It just takes a while. To help quicker characterize the clusters, I assign three general levels, i.e. High, Medium and Low, to each feature in the above table. See the new table below:

In [105]:
def number2level(X):
    """Convert a number in [0, 1] to three general levels - Low, Medium, High. 
    Note that the ranges of the levels are not the same.
    """
    if X >= 3/4:
        level = 'High'
    elif 1/4 <= X <3/4:
        level = 'Medium'
    else:
        level = 'Low'
    
    return level

Most of the neighborhoods in Cluster_0 are located in the outer city. They are not densely populated by people or venues. However, they are well-established since there are many venues in the Shop & Service category.

Cluster_4 is a bit similar with Cluster_0 in that it's also in the outer city and even outer than Cluster_0. The population is not dense and there are few venues for people to hang out. A major difference is that the housing price in Cluster_4 is low and the lowest in the whole city.

Most of the neighborhoods in Cluster_2 are located on the border of inner and outer Oslo. Like Cluster_0 and Cluster_4, it's also sparsely populated. However, it's very well-established since it has high level in Professional & Other Places, Shop & Service and Travel & Transport. And the number of venues for Arts & Entertainment, Food and Outdoors & Recreation are very fair. It's a well-balanced cluster.

Cluster_5 is a bit similar with Cluster_2. The major difference from Cluster_2 and any other cluster is that it has a university around (Just bear with it if you know there are other universities). And the housing price is high. Catchment area?

Cluster_1, Cluster_3 and Cluster_6 form the inner city and they share a lot in common. They are all densely populated. There are also lots of places about Arts & Entertainment and Food for people to hang out. Here are their differences: Cluster_3 has lots of nightlife spot. It's haven for young people. In fact, the young people come from different counties and cultural background. And the housing price is not as high as Cluster_1 and Cluster_6. Cluster_6 has a lot of venues about Arts & Entertainment, e.g. Vigeland Park, Viking Ship Museum and lots of tourists!

Results - Predicting where you will live in Oslo ¶

We already know which neighborhoods in Oslo are alike. Now it's time to predict which neighborhoods you are going to like in Oslo. Suppose you are currently live at Chelsea, London and you like there.

Collecting data of Chelsea¶

Chelsea is an affluent area of South West London, bounded to the south by the River Thames. I choose Chelsea not because it's full of wealth but because one of my favorite football player N'Golo Kanté plays for Chelsea Football Club.

To predict the similarity between any neighborhood and the neighborhoods in Oslo, I need data of this neighborhood that has to have all the features as the data of the neighborhoods in Oslo has.

The population density can be found at Wikipedia, which gives 13000/km2.

The housing price can be found at www.ons.gov.uk, which shows that one square meter of floor space – an area about the size of a red phone box – costs almost £19,439 in Kensington and Chelsea.

Discussion ¶

From the above prediction, the k-means clustering model seems working reasonably well on segmenting the neighborhoods in Oslo and providing suggestions to new comers. Nevertheless, there are ways to improve its performance. For example, as mentioned earlier in this report, the venue data from Foursquare is not very thorough. If the venue of OsloMet University is included in the venue data, perhaps Homansbyen will be less similar with Chelsea. So more thorough data of the venues can better characterize the neighborhoods. One possible solution is resort to Google Maps for more venues (This project requires to use Foursquare data so I am not going to try in this project).

To make such service more practical, the scope of the data can be extended to the Great Oslo Region, because many people work in Oslo city area and live in cities or towns such as Sandvika and Lillestrøm. However, this will be a much larger and complex project.

The codes for the project are far from production, though they can be ran without error so far. In the case of e.g. adding new features and predicting more examples, the codes need to be always fast, resilient and free of error. This could be a future direction.

Conclusion ¶

In this project, I have built a recommender that provides suggestions for people who are going to move to Oslo and looking for a general area to live. The recommendation is based on the similarities between the current neighborhood and the neighborhoods in Oslo. To obtain such similarities, I have collected data of the neighborhoods in Oslo from difference websites such as Oslo Kommune and Foursquare. The features of the data include population, area size, coordinates, and nearby venues. After collecting and cleaning the data, I have performed EDA on the features and found some observations such as neighborhoods with smaller area sizes tend to be more densely populated. Through EDA, I have identified a few features for segmenting the neighborhoods in Oslo. K-means clustering algorithm was selected to perform the segmentation task. It has been found that all the neighborhoods can be well segmented into seven clusters. I have provided detailed explanation to justify the clustering result and characterize the clusters. Finally, I have chosen a virtual person currently living at Chelsea, London to test my k-means clustering model, which suggests Chelsea is similar with the neighborhoods in Frogner, Oslo.
